      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>.</p>
<p>I have struggled with my weight and sugar cravings for as long as I can remember.<img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-303" title="mother-and-daughter" src="http://www.foodandsugaraddiction.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/07/mother-and-daughter-232x300.png" alt="mother-and-daughter" width="232" height="300" /></p>
<p>I remember that mashed potatoes were and still are my ultimate comfort food.  2nd place being home made macaroni and cheese.</p>
<p>I remember that chicken was a major staple at the dinner table when I was a kid.</p>
<p>I remember that dessert was only a Sunday night thing.</p>
<p>I remember that crazy feeling in my head when I was a kid and looked for what ever sweet I could get my hands on.</p>
<p>I remember my father telling me when he was a kid, living thru the depression and having 10 siblings all living in the same house that desserts were scarce.  He used to make sugar sandwiches.  This was my first &#8220;ah ha&#8221; moment.  This was how I could get the sugar I was craving!  I started making bread/butter/sugar sandwiches to get my &#8220;fix&#8221;.  Then one of my friends from school said, &#8220;You need to toast it, melt the butter and put brown sugar and cinnamon on it! It&#8217;s delicious like that.&#8221;</p>
<p>That was stuff that was in the house and was readily available.  Today things are a bit different for our own kids.  Sugar is everywhere.  Getting a sugar fix is realitively easy.</p>
<p>My daughter is 12.  Starting that puberty stuff.  This is when <strong>my</strong> sugar issues first exploded.  I do <strong>NOT</strong> want my daughter to have to go thru a life time of crazy sugar feelings.</p>
<p>I have been noticing some wild fluctuations in her moods the last little while.  At first I thought it was just hormones.  I let it go for quite a while.  Then I started to have her journal her food and feelings.  What a <strong>&#8220;WOW&#8221;</strong> moment for this mom!</p>
<p>We sat down and had a heart to heart talk about how she was feeling and if she liked it.  The answer as you can guess was &#8220;no&#8221;.   I also asked her if she wanted help with controlling all that crazy feeling that was going on in her head.  She had a bit of a cry and admitted that she really wanted help with it.</p>
<p>I wanted her to feel like this was a sugar issue and not a weight issue.  But the weight issue came up after a shopping trip for new summer clothing.  She says it fits, I say its too small.  I dont like seeing anything tight around her belly.  She doesnt either, but then the top is too big.  There was a little melt down about the fact that she needs to buy xl t-shirts to fit her belly and its still too big ontop.  Ok&#8230;mom to the rescue again.</p>
<p>This was and still is so hard!  I don&#8217;t want her to focus on her weight.  I&#8217;ve told her that if she doesn&#8217;t gain any weight over the summer, by August alot of her belly will be gone.  In her mind, both the crazy feelings and the little bit of belly are major issues and she wants it all to be gone.  Ok, I get that.  Thankfully the food program I have put together for her is keeping her moods much more stable.  She isnt liking that she can&#8217;t have all the sugar filled goodies all day long like she used to.  But she isn&#8217;t deprived either.  We&#8217;ve brought back dessert.  Whether its a sugar free popsicle or a home made apple crisp.  It&#8217;s still there, and she is able to see that she still gets to have a sweet once a day.  She just has to have it after a meal.  Period.</p>
<p>Last night created a bit of a meltdown because she doesn&#8217;t like being denied.  But this morning she got up and got on the scale and told me with a bit of question in her voice what she weighed.  Turns out my little girl has lost 1/2 a pound.</p>
<p>I am so proud of her!  But it is a fine line we walk isn&#8217;t it.  Give her the tools and encouragement to do it on her own.  Let her fly, pick her up when she falls, hold her hand when she needs guidance. Always tell her she is beautiful and will always be my baby girl.</p>
<p>I would love for the sugar crazies to stop here!  Have the right tools to take it under control and leave it there.</p>
<p>One step at a time.</p>
<p>.</p>
