      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I met this very lovely lady on Twitter!  She is way over on the other side of the world, but she &#8220;knows&#8221; what I am going thru.</p>
<p>She offered to share her story with me quite a while ago.  Emailed it to me, and when I asked if I could share it with the world she very graciously agreed to let me.</p>
<p>You may know her as Selena or on Twitter as <a href="http://twitter.com/Spreiki">@Spreiki<br />
</a></p>
<p>Here is her story&#8230;</p>
<blockquote><p>This is my story.</p>
<p>One of my earliest memories was sneaking into the kitchen when my mum<br />
wasn’t looking and making myself a white bread and margarine sandwich -<br />
I’m talking from before I was 10 years old.  And I‘d do this a lot.  When<br />
I wasn&#8217;t doing that, I was eating lashings of chocolate whenever I could.</p>
<p>When I was at Junior school my mum told the cook to just give me a piece<br />
of fruit for my pudding as I wasn’t just having seconds, I was having<br />
thirds of pudding every single day.  Boy was I mad at her!</p>
<p>When I left school I fell into a job, I had no motivation, I was depressed<br />
and I would literally binge all day long.  If it wasn‘t nailed down, I<br />
would eat it.  I would eat sugared cereal straight out of the pack while<br />
sitting on the floor and biscuits all day long.  I could not stop.</p>
<p>My confidence was through the floor despite being smart.  I was<br />
rebellious, withdrawn, oh you name it, I had it.  I didn’t know who I was<br />
or what I wanted from life and thought that losing weight was the answer<br />
to all the worldly ills - oh how wrong could I have been LOL - I was just<br />
sugar sensitive!  I lost a lot of weight with Weight Watchers and then<br />
regained 8.5 pounds in two weeks after rediscovering chocolate.  The<br />
following week I lost all of that weight plus another half a pound.  I<br />
couldn’t see how crazy it was.</p>
<p>I discovered the book Potatoes not Prozac as soon as it came out - by then<br />
I had pretty much every diet book going!  I read it and connected with it<br />
straight away but I wanted a quick fix.  I didn’t want to wait - I wanted<br />
it all NOW.  It sat back on my shelf for another five years and I had to<br />
explore plenty more avenues before I would come back to it again.</p>
<p>When I wasn’t eating sugar and whites I was drinking.  I lost whole<br />
weekends.  On another detour I lost 80 pounds before I threw my hands in<br />
the air and decided, enough was enough.  It took me another two years of<br />
faffing around with the program before I got past step 2 (there are 7<br />
steps on the program).</p>
<p>Around step 3 I was starting to feel good.  I had never travelled on my<br />
own before but I wanted to go to the Radiant Recovery Brits meeting in<br />
London (100 miles away) but couldn’t figure out how I could possibly do<br />
it.  I was petrified!  I posted about it on the website and I was given<br />
some baby steps and websites that I might look at for trains etc.  I went<br />
and had a fabulous time!</p>
<p>My program progressed quite swiftly after that initial meeting and I<br />
detoxed totally by accident in June - the sugar had been missing for 3<br />
days before I had even realised.  I was planning on detoxing after the<br />
summer holidays so that I could still have ice creams with my children but<br />
my body had other ideas!  Talk about a non-event.</p>
<p>Since then I&#8217;ve flown to Amsterdam on my own to meet up with a couple of<br />
radiant pals and we flew on to Boston together for a seminar in Maine.<br />
Just a year ago I would never have entertained the idea - not in a million<br />
years - but now it just seems a totally natural thing to do - no fuss,<br />
just functional.</p>
<p>I am now happy the vast majority of the time, I eat just three meals a<br />
day, I can&#8217;t remember the last time I binges, I am filled with joy - I<br />
know what full feels like, I wear make-up again to please myself (not<br />
others!), and I am moving my body more and meditating.  If something’s not<br />
right, I know how to fix it or know where to find the advice to do so.  I<br />
am starting to dream again, to do the things that are important to me, to<br />
be who *I* am, not someone who the media says I ought to be.</p>
<p>I used to inhale whole doughnuts.  But now when I look in cake shops, they<br />
do not call to me any more.  It is an amazing feeling!</p>
<p>Well, that’s me .  I&#8217;m not too sure why I felt the need to tell you<br />
my story, but I hope that something in my email has helped.</p>
<p>All the very best,</p>
<p>Selena</p></blockquote>
<p>One of the comments Selena made inparticular that made me sit up and take notice was&#8230;</p>
<p>.</p>
<blockquote><p>When I wasn’t eating sugar and whites I was drinking.</p></blockquote>
<p>.<br />
I truly believe there is a connection between sugar addiction and alcohol addiction.   Out of all the addictions in my very large family, I got the sugar/food addiction.  Alcohol for the most part (except in my younger years) only goes so far.   Only because I don&#8217;t like not being able to function the next day.  But you see&#8230;.I can binge on cakes, cookies, chocolate, candy until my belly feels like it is going to explode and I can still function.   No hangover or wicked headache.</p>
<p>Maybe they need to come up with a pill for sugar addicts like the Topamax pill for alcoholics?  Yes I know there isn&#8217;t a magic pill, but I will always look for one!</p>
<p>I hope you were able to gain some insight into your own issues from this post.  I also hope you can see that you are not alone in your struggle.  There are many of us out there fighting the same fight.</p>
<p>If you would like your story, with us please send it to me,  robin at foodandsugaraddiction .com.  Everyone who is fighting against food and sugar has a story.  You may be at goal weight, or working on getting there.  Where ever you are in your journey, I would love to hear from you.</p>
<p>I wish you peace and sane eating in your journey.</p>
