      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Sometimes we think we are going mad.  The sugar cravings are so bad, that you are eating things you would never think of.<img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-223" title="sugar-cubes1" src="http://www.foodandsugaraddiction.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/05/sugar-cubes1-300x199.jpg" alt="sugar-cubes1" width="300" height="199" /></p>
<p>That brain of ours has ways of getting the body what it craves.  If it means sprinkling brown sugar on buttered bread&#8230;.because that&#8217;s all that&#8217;s in the house.  That&#8217;s what you do.</p>
<p>Maybe you&#8217;ve sworn off sugar, but you are replacing it with something else.  Ive done this many times. </p>
<p>Quit drinking coffee, only to replace it with chocolate.</p>
<p>Quit eating sugar only to replace it with wine (enough to make the neighbours comment when they see the recycling box)</p>
<p>One of MY biggest contributors to my sugar issues were: PCOS, Yeast gone Wild and Heredity!  Lets not forget that sugar addiction and alcoholism are very closely linked. </p>
<p>Have you noticed that recovering alcoholics eat quite a bit of sugary candies or large amounts of carbs? </p>
<p>Here is my take on this&#8230;if you have alcoholism in your family, you already know that this is a disease.  You also know that it is hereditary.  If you have sugar addicts or alcoholism on either side of your family you are at risk!  Lucky me, one side has both sugar and alcoholism and the other has food and sugar addiction.  I lucked out didn&#8217;t I!?!?!</p>
<p>So knowing all this, I have a better understanding of where I come from.  I also understand that it isn&#8217;t my fault.  What is my fault is how I am choosing to deal with it.  Getting the cravings under control can be done!</p>
<h2>Yeast!</h2>
<p>Do you have too much of it?  I <strong>DO NOT</strong> suggest you eat yogurt to control it.  Why?  Because yeast feeds on sugar, and today&#8217;s yogurts are full of sugar.  If they aren&#8217;t they are full of sweeteners which fool your body into thinking it&#8217;s been given sugar and still sends out the insulin to take care of it.  Results: you get fatter!</p>
<p>Yeast feeds on sugar!  So stop feeding it!  One of the best indicators of too much yeast is recurring yeast infections.  If you find you need a trip to the drug store every couple months for &#8220;stuff&#8221;.  You definitely have too much yeast in your system.</p>
<h2>How Do You Stop Feeding Yeast?</h2>
<ol>
<li>ingest absolutely NO sugar of any kind!</li>
<li>ingest absolutely NO sweetener of any kind!</li>
<li>do not eat anything fermented eg. cheese, vinegar, wine, bread, beer, pickles, yogurt, etc,</li>
<li>do not eat any type of grain &#8230;these are usually sitting in a silo someplace growing mold</li>
<li>do not eat any mold of any kind eg. blue cheese, mushrooms, sour cream, sour milk, dried fruits, pickled or smoked meats, etc.</li>
</ol>
<p>What you do want to eat is fresh vegetables and lean clean protein. </p>
<p>If you are missing your vinegar in your salad dressing, use lemon juice instead.</p>
<h2>How long should I eat like this?</h2>
<p>1 to 2 weeks!  Then start adding back into your diet <strong>slowly  </strong>lower carb choices.  Such as cheese, pickles, mushrooms, mustard etc.  If you start to notice the cravings coming back, cut those items back out.  Repeat the process until you feel confident that the yeast is no longer telling you what to do.</p>
<h2>What then?</h2>
<p>Make a commitment to yourself to keep sugar and white flour out of your diet.  Sometimes it is hidden and you don&#8217;t even realize you&#8217;ve eaten it.  Like the time Mike and I came home from Applebee&#8217;s.  I had just finished a huge taco salad.  When I got home I found myself standing infront of the fridge looking for something to eat.  There is no way I should have been hungry.  No way at all!!  But I was&#8230;or at least that is what my brain was telling me.  It was a crazy hunger too.  That is when I realized I had eaten something in that salad that was laced with sugar and I didn&#8217;t even notice it.</p>
<p> </p>
<p>This is just the first step&#8230;.but it will get you started!</p>
