      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>My husband and I were out for a ride tonight, and my phone buzzed.  It was an email from a friend describing how much fun he and a large group of friends had today.  What did they do?  They went on a canoe trip. <img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-189" title="canoe" src="http://www.foodandsugaraddiction.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/05/canoe-300x200.jpg" alt="canoe" width="300" height="200" /></p>
<p>Some of you who know me, know that I come from a place where canoeing, fishing, camping and large fresh water lakes are a way of life.  Something I used to do all the time. </p>
<p>Fast forward 13 years, and here I am too big to enjoy what I used to love to do.  No, I&#8217;m not too big, but I &#8220;feel&#8221; too big.  Does that make sense?  I&#8217;ve put myself in the way of myself and what I enjoy.  Is it an excuse?  Yes I suppose it is.  But would you put yourself thru something that made you feel unbearably uncomfortable?  I also suppose after another 20lbs gone, I will feel a bit better in my skin and I will come a bit more out of my shell.</p>
<p>Here is what I am looking forward to&#8230;</p>
<ol>
<li>being able to lift a kayak on my own to put it ontop of the car</li>
<li>going on canoe and camping trips</li>
<li>fitting in the rides at 6 flags</li>
<li>clothing that fits properly</li>
<li>ditching the sweat shirts I&#8217;ve been wearing all winter because that was all that fit and was warm</li>
<li>not sucking wind when I climb more than 3 flights of stairs</li>
<li>sex! (its always better when you aren&#8217;t worried about what you look like isn&#8217;t it?!!!)</li>
<li>gardening that doesn&#8217;t take me weeks instead of a weekend.</li>
<li>bike riding with my daughter this summer</li>
<li>feeling pretty and sexy (most days its easy to ignore the mirror and the extra 100lbs)</li>
<li>moving into the &#8220;overweight&#8221; category from &#8220;<strong>obese</strong>&#8220;</li>
</ol>
<p>This isn&#8217;t a list of &#8220;what are you waiting for&#8217;s&#8221;.  It is a realistic list of things you have a difficult time doing now, and knowing that when the pounds start coming off, you will feel better doing.</p>
<p>How about you&#8230;.what are you looking forward to?</p>
<p>While I&#8217;m at it&#8230;what did you do today to make yourself feel absolutely wonderful?  I went to work out, I did good.  Felt good!  But then I was tired LOL.  Maybe I&#8217;ll get a delayed &#8220;WooHoo&#8221; feeling tomorrow?</p>
<p> </p>
<p>.</p>
