      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p> </p>
<h2>&#8230;and What We Hide</h2>
<p>One of my very first memories of having uncontrollable sugar cravings was when I was about 9 yrs old.  The need for sugar was so bad, I walked to the corner grocery store and stuffed my pockets with prepackaged butter tarts! I ate every single one of them on the way home and I felt so much better.  Now if you don&#8217;t know what a butter tart is, it is basically liquefied brown sugar, corn syrup, butter and egg in a pastry shell.  Maybe toss in a few raisins too.  So I got my fix.</p>
<p>But this was about the time I started having serious issues. </p>
<p>I&#8217;d make toast and load it up with butter and then put brown sugar all over it.<img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-146" title="sugar-cubes" src="http://www.foodandsugaraddiction.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/05/sugar-cubes-300x225.jpg" alt="sugar-cubes" width="300" height="225" /></p>
<p>I&#8217;d just butter bread and sprinkle white sugar on the butter.</p>
<p>Make popcorn, and melt butter with brown sugar mixed in and pour that all over the popcorn.</p>
<p>Any cookies mom made usually only lasted in the house for about 2 days.</p>
<p>When you are a kid, and you don&#8217;t have any money, you find ways to get your sugar fix. </p>
<p> </p>
<p>I&#8217;m older now&#8230;.I should know better right?  No, that gnawing in my brain is still there.  But now I know how to control it with a better diet!</p>
<p>Hiding things and telling lies seem to be a common denominator for an <strong>addict</strong>.  No matter what it is.  Drugs, alcohol, sex, food!</p>
<p>When was the last time you hid what you were eating? Do you wait until your spouse/partner goes to bed?  Do you raid the cupboards and fridge then?  Do you sneak down to the fridge and eat the last of the pizza?  Do you eat the entire cake and tell your spouse/partner that you thru it out because you were starting your diet that day?  Have you sat in the wegmans parking lot after grocery shopping, and stuffed marshmallows in your face, or chocolate, or a bag of cookies, or an entire bag of potato chips, or even a whole box of ice cream treats you knew you could get all in before you got home with your &#8220;diet food&#8221;?</p>
<p>Have you gone running errands, and made a pit stop at your favorite &#8220;supplier&#8221; and loaded up with goodies to eat in the car?  Have you gone out just to eat the sugary/cakey items you didn&#8217;t want anyone else to know about.  Have you eaten everything in your car just so you didn&#8217;t have to share it when you got home?  Hidden food in your purse so you could sneak eat it when no one was looking?</p>
<p>Have you lied to yourself?  Telling yourself you really don&#8217;t eat that much. </p>
<p>Telling your spouse/partner that you didn&#8217;t have any dessert or that you ate what you were suppose to.</p>
<p>Telling your child you cannot go to the fairgrounds, because you get too dizzy when you go on the rides.  When the truth is y0u don&#8217;t fit in the rides.</p>
<p>Making excuses to your spouse/partner for not wanting to attend an event just because you feel too fat and ashamed.</p>
<p>Telling your child you just don&#8217;t want to go for a bike ride, because you are too tired.  Truth is, you feel huge ontop of that bike frame.</p>
<p>Not working out when you told your spouse/partner that you did.</p>
<p>We&#8217;ve all done it.  In one form or another.  If you are an addict, you understand.  You may be reading this and think&#8230;.this woman is off  her friggin rocker!  Then you probably don&#8217;t have a food addiction.  But if you get it, if you cried or teared when you read this, because you understand&#8230;.then we are both in the same boat. </p>
<h3>How Are You Coping?</h3>
<p>What changes have you made?  Some of the things I have done include:</p>
<ul>
<li>buying a new smaller purse that doesn&#8217;t zip closed</li>
<li>taking Mike with me when I want to go out in the evenings (no matter how much he complains)</li>
<li>stopped eating in the car</li>
<li>going to bed at the same time or before Mike (keeps me out of the kitchen)</li>
<li>stopped eating after 8pm!</li>
<li>changed my food plan to help combat the sugar cravings</li>
<li>working &#8220;<a href="http://astore.amazon.com/buffagraph0b-20/detail/0848731735" target="_blank">The Beck Diet Solution</a>&#8220;</li>
<li>planning out my weeks worth of food</li>
<li>cooking on weekends to make sure I eat what is planned</li>
<li>started working with a personal trainer.  One that cares!  She may not understand the addiction (I don&#8217;t really know) But she cares enough to help any way she can.</li>
<li>when Mike wants some sort of &#8220;goodie&#8221; he&#8217;ll ask if it&#8217;s ok with me.  He wants to know if him eating it will bother me. </li>
<li>telling Mike what I am going thru.  What issues I may be having that day.  He may not know what to do about it, but he &#8220;gets it&#8221;.  That in itself has been very helpful.</li>
</ul>
<p>My plan this summer is to get on that bicycle and bike around with my daughter!  Get out to darien lake and put my butt in those dizzy rides and have a blast with my daughter!  Get out in a kayak and paddle around the waters in the buffalo area. </p>
<p>Making food a non-issue! </p>
<p><strong>It&#8217;s time to get back to living!</strong></p>
