      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p> </p>
<p>It has been a little bit of a struggle, but I have my cravings under control.  I know how to do it, I know what effects them, I just need to apply my research and knowledge.  Sometimes however the very last thing I want to do is to do what I am &#8220;suppose&#8221; to do.  Go figure.<img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-92" title="fat-vs-muscle" src="http://www.foodandsugaraddiction.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/05/fat-vs-muscle-300x178.jpg" alt="fat-vs-muscle" width="300" height="178" /></p>
<p>Here you can see 5 pounds of fat and 5 pounds of muscle.  Since starting this blog I&#8217;ve lost 10 of those fat pounds!  (2 of those chunks!) Can you image?  Stack 10 pounds of butter 2 x 2 and that&#8217;s what is gone.  Sometimes we loose sight of just how much 1 pound looks like.  When dealing with large amounts of weightloss, we tend to think in large volume.  So remember those stacked butter pounds every time you get on the scale.</p>
<p>You probably read in my last post that I will be working with Michelle.  She is going to be helping me build strong muscle, and helping to get me much leaner.  One of the keys to fighting <strong>obesity </strong>is building muscle.  I want my own little fat burners attached right to my very own body.  No drugs, no pills, no magic potions to burn the fat.  I am going to be building muscle that is going to burn that crud in my sleep!  How much easier can that be?  Yah, ok&#8230;&#8230;the fat burning during my sleep will be easy.  The muscle building will be a little more difficult.  That&#8217;s ok.</p>
<p>What did I do this week to help take the edge off my <strong>sugar addiction</strong> and get the<strong> food addiction</strong> under control<strong>?</strong></p>
<p>1.  Cut all grains/fruits/sugar out of my diet.</p>
<p>2.  Drank gallons of water.</p>
<p>3.  Absolutely no food after 8pm. (the kitchen is closed!)</p>
<p>4.  Pre-made/planned all lunches for the week.</p>
<p>5.  Cleaned/washed/stored the veggies I was going to be eating for snacks</p>
<p>6.  Cleaned/washed/stored the lettuce I bought.  Rather than using the pre-bagged stuff that has a funky flavor!</p>
<p>7.  I worked out!!!</p>
<h3>Smart choices I made this past week.  </h3>
<p>1.  Skipped lunch at networking meeting and ate what I had planned for myself</p>
<p>2.  When we ate out at Kosta&#8217;s tonight, I asked our server for a take-away box as soon as she brought me my souvlaki.  Half my meal went right into the box before I started eating or putting any dressing ontop of it.  I now have tomorrows lunch!</p>
<h3>Plans/Prep for next week</h3>
<p>1.  New celery container for the fridge was purchased</p>
<p>2.  New  lettuce/veggie keeper was purchased so I can prep more lettuce/veggies at one time</p>
<p>3.  New juice container was purchased so I can start making my iced green tea in batches (Mike snagged my old container)</p>
<p>4.  Made appointment with <a href="http://www.healthandfitsolutions.com" target="_blank">Michelle</a> for Monday morning. </p>
<p>5.  New flavor soup needs to be made for next week&#8217;s lunchs and I think I might like some deviled eggs to have with my protein shakes in the mornings. (I&#8217;ll post the recipe after I decide what I might fancy)</p>
<p>6.  Grocery shopping!!</p>
<h3>Plan for success!</h3>
<p> </p>
